Photos TBA. **rarely seen and difficult-to-detect migrant. I believe this is a continuing immature first photographed by Alena and likely the slim, chestnut-brown body with wings lacking the intense rufous wing patch cuckoo I flushed a day or so prior to her seeing this bird. I'm sure he's come to know me well as I've searched for him unsuccessfully the last few days.  Slender, delicate and athletically built cuckoo, with darker brown tones to body, a hint of rufous to the wings, and a thin tail lacking conspicuous markings. Immature bird with pale yellow orbital ring. Slender all dark bill.  Caught a glimpse of movement as the bird came in high from the North, flushed by another entity which I did not observe.  Actually quite mobile, flying from tree to tree. Wary and shy of my presence but tolerating with slow and precise movements. At one point the bird flew from its high hickory into small dense trees about 15 feet off the ground and less distance than that away from me, providing a great experience! I lost track of it shortly after. Plenty of tent caterpillar nests around, but I did not witness him utilizing any. One of my favorite species! I hope to see an adult soon.

Observation Details: Unusually conspicuous. Singing need boardwalk for several minutes, sometimes in almost fully view. Song a classic “ku-ku-ku-ku” repeated several times. Volume varied from soft, almost inaudible song to loud, far-carrying bouts. Good views allowed looks of the bird’s enlarged throat and breast while singing. Twice harassed by EAKI. Briefly landed low in alder just off the boardwalk and gave a handful of quick, harsh calls with bill gaped (reacting to camera shutter?). This perch allowed for 2-3 minutes of close observation where the bird’s curved bill and striking red eye ring could be fully appreciated. The bird remained in the area singing from various perches until I departed.

Observation Details: This bird has been singing along the driveway for a few weeks now, the property owners didn't know what kind of bird it was, they had heard it incessantly without seeing it. The Levy's contacted Bernard Forsythe. who was able to confirm it's identity yesterday. Today we were able to both hear and see the Black Billed Cuckoo, a lifer for all three of us. The cuckoo had an all black bill, large black eye, brown back, no reddish in the wings, white breast and belly, and the long tail was greyish underneath with small white bars or tips on the feathers.

Photos TBA. **Very rare and often difficult to detect migrant in both seasons.  Finally, after nearly 3 hours this visit and multiple other visits! Amazing this bird has lingered this long. Weather can do this, and there's plenty of caterpillars to eat!  Just after I told Chelsea, "Well, I'll check the center path one more time before leaving. Got eyes on a YBCU, which was a lifer for her, when I suddenly caught movement to my right. Low and behold the BBCU foraging in a tent about 15 feet off the ground directly above the path! Fed for a few moments before taking flight towards the center of the park. Sometimes you really just gotta give it a few more minutes! Locality: PNM das Dunas da Lagoa da Conceição--Lagoas
Observation Details: Extraída da rede de neblina e fotografada. Identificado pelo bico escuro uniforme, maxila superior preta; anel perioftálmico amarelo, característico dos indivíduos jovens ou fora do período reprodutivo presentes nos locais de invernada. Segundo registro para o Brasil, o primeiro para região sul do país e Santa Catarina, possivelmente o mesmo indivíduo ou bando realizando movimentos migratórios encontrado no Rio do Janeiro nesse mês, no dia 4 (ver registro: www.wikiaves.com.br/5717727), feito por Guilherme Serpa. Fora de sua rota de migração usual no noroeste de América do Sul, da Colômbia,Venezuela e Peru; possivelmente um errante. Por fazerem parte de um projeto que avalia a microbiota do animal, foram coletados dois Swabs, de cloaca e orofaringe. Posteriormente a coleta, o animal foi Anilhado (Anilha CEMAVE código G131497) e solto. Autorizações de pesquisa: SISBIO, CEMAVE, IMA e FLORAM.

Observation Details: I heard a bird call that I could not identify so I used my Merlin Bird ID app and it identified it as a Black-billed Cuckoo. I tried a couple of times and it kept identifying it as the cuckoo.  I played back the song to see what it sounded like and immediately a fairly good sized bird flew over my head and into a nearby tree.  The sun was down behind the trees so it was hard to get a good picture, but as I was trying, my sister looked up the ID info for the cuckoo.  The bird we were watching had a long slightly curved black bill, a very long slender tail with white showing on the tips. the belly was a plain white and the back was dark. In one of the pictures the red around the eye is visible when zoomed in.  We watched it move from tree to tree and call for about 15-20 minutes before it moved off into the woods.

Observation Details: Watched pair foraging along river for 20 minutes. Male summoned mate from across river with a couple of quiet calls, then flew over and copulated with her while holding a cranefly in his bill. Pair then continued foraging together, not more than 6-7 metres apart. Amazing sight.

Initially submitted as  Black-billed Cuckoo/Yellow-billed Cuckoo. Had now been accepted by Ebird reviewer as Black billed Cuckoo. Pros for juvenile black: the all-black bill, pale orbital ring, and pale edging on the feathers.  Plus it seems a little late in the season for juvenile yellows to still have a black bill.  Pros for juvenile yellow: also the black bill, rufous patch on the wings, and black-billed is rare on the coast. Unfortunately didn't get a look at the undertail before it flew off.  We were clued into this bird by his call which was 3 notes and did not vary in pitch or cadence. Observed in line of trees across from spawar building before it flew onto a power line. After perching for a minute or so, it flew west and we could not relocate the bird. See pictures.

Photographed along edge of parking lot as it moved towards fenceline. Red orbital skin, gray forehead, gray mandible and black maxilla, fine white/black bands on underside of tail (vs broad white spots of Yellow-billed Cuckoo). Unexpected rare migrant that showed very well.

Loch, just past Glen Span Arch. One young cuckoo seen hunting, feeding, drinking and resting in eye level. I had never seen a cuckoo this well. Large slender bird with long tail with very faint markings, thin blackish bill, no red on eye ring, some rufous color on head and primaries. The other cuckoo was only seen briefly when it interacted with this one. I observed this young bird between 12:50 and 1:20 pm after both Cuckoos were missing for half hour or so. A BB Cuckoo was first reported a little after 9 am by Philippe S in further E at second cut and eventually joined by another BB Cuckoo, and seen by many birders since then. Observation Details: Juvenile bird and with no tail.  All black bill, slightly grayish on lower mandible closest to base.  Virtually no rusty coloration on wings as seen in photos, or maybe none at all.  Face and cheek white, contrasting with cap which I think would makes this a juv. YBCU.  BBCU should be buffy/tan colored through throat and not sharply contrasting with gray on head?  YBCU juv. known to have all black bill.  Bill also maybe slightly chunkier than what BBCU would have?  Unsure of species, any comments welcome.  Knut had a 2nd heard only BBCU calling that I heard too little of to say that I "heard it".    9/5/17 updated to BBCU from the BBCU/YBCU that I had previously listed it as.  Email with ME reviewer, Louis Bevier in which he suggests the following:    "That cuckoo appears to be a Black-billed Cuckoo. You seemed to have eliminated that species for a lack of buff on the throat, but that is only a pale wash on some. Also, the yellow on the mandible of juvenile Yellow-billed is more restricted but rarely (if ever?) totally absent. The bill color is perfect for Black-billed. The real clincher has to be the wings, which in your one profile shot show enough to determine that there is no rufous in the primaries. That is consistent with Black-billed and wrong for Yellow-billed.  I hope that helps you. I recommend putting this in as Black-billed."  KS reviewer J. King also felt BBCU a better match and suggested the following:  "In juvenile plumage (lasts from fledgling until a partial molt that occurs after a few months of life) YBCU should have some red in the flight feathers and coverts. Regarding BBCU, it says "feathers of nape, scapulars, wing coverts, and rump tipped with dull grayish white". It also says the tail of the BBCU is particularly short."

Continuing bird, first reported by Teresa Dolman this morning, and then refound by Ken Orich this afternoon. Recording and photos taken. Patch species #204.  For those considering looking for this bird, I would suggest an early morning or late evening visit, if possible. It is more likely that the cuckoo will be active and vocalizing at these times. Also—and importantly—you may avoid a scenario in which you find yourself dragging your body up a sun-scorched coulee face at 36° wishing for the sweet release of death just a little more with each pitiful step.

Immature black-billed cuckoo with a black upper mandible and a grayish-black lower mandible. It has a subtle eye ring and grayish wings, with some brown tones on the primary feathers but lacking the distinctive rusty hues of the yellow-billed cuckoo. The tail is grayish, and its underside lacks the large spots typical of the yellow-billed cuckoo. This bird was observed in cypress trees in a parking lot and among low, shrubby vegetation along a ditch.

Loch, just past Glen Span Arch. One young cuckoo seen hunting, feeding, drinking and resting in eye level. I had never seen a cuckoo this well. Large slender bird with long tail with very faint markings, thin blackish bill, no red on eye ring, some rufous color on head and primaries. The other cuckoo was only seen briefly when it interacted with this one. I observed this young bird between 12:50 and 1:20 pm after both Cuckoos were missing for half hour or so. A BB Cuckoo was first reported a little after 9 am by Philippe S in further E at second cut and eventually joined by another BB Cuckoo, and seen by many birders since then. Photos TBA. **rarely seen and difficult-to-detect migrant. I believe this is a continuing immature first photographed by Alena and likely the slim, chestnut-brown body with wings lacking the intense rufous wing patch cuckoo I flushed a day or so prior to her seeing this bird. I'm sure he's come to know me well as I've searched for him unsuccessfully the last few days.  Slender, delicate and athletically built cuckoo, with darker brown tones to body, a hint of rufous to the wings, and a thin tail lacking conspicuous markings. Immature bird with pale yellow orbital ring. Slender all dark bill.  Caught a glimpse of movement as the bird came in high from the North, flushed by another entity which I did not observe.  Actually quite mobile, flying from tree to tree. Wary and shy of my presence but tolerating with slow and precise movements. At one point the bird flew from its high hickory into small dense trees about 15 feet off the ground and less distance than that away from me, providing a great experience! I lost track of it shortly after. Plenty of tent caterpillar nests around, but I did not witness him utilizing any. One of my favorite species! I hope to see an adult soon.

Observation Details: Spotted and photographed one individual that remained unmoving on a horizontal branch high in a tree for ~ 8 -10 minutes. As we were starting to move away and look in a different direction, a second cuckoo flew into the tree where the first bird was perched, and there was a sudden flurry of interaction between the two. Not seen well due to distance and foliage. One of the birds flew off, and the remaining cuckoo (presumably the first bird we saw) was observed facing the direction where the other bird had flown. It was repeatedly raising and lowering its wings in a slow-motion flutter before flying off in the direction of the second bird. Suspect we missed seeing an adult feeding the immature bird that was photographed.

Observation Details: Heard one coo-coo-cooing distantly upon getting out of the car. Faster and not as deep as a Least Bittern. This bird flew into a nearby tree and stayed there more or less motionless for @ five (5) minutes with nesting material in it's beak. Another bird was seen closer to the parking area on the way back, which landed a smaller tree alongside the path.  Adult Black-billed Cuckoos have a red orbital ring and because of this resemble Killdeer in the eye. Adult  Yellow-billed Cuckoo have a yellow orbital ring in addition to a yellow bill.

Heard "coo-coo-coo" in the distance about 5 times, but I assumed it was a Least Bittern--after hacking through the brush I came to an old beaver pond with a little cattail marsh, so the habitat was not as marginal for bitterns as I first thought. After moving farther along the wetland for about 10 minutes, I heard it again, but this time it was clearly not coming from the wetland but the low trees adjacent. I was able to find the cuckoo adjacent to a tent caterpillar nest, and I noted the black bill and red eye-ring. The cuckoo was always facing away, so I couldn't see underside of the tail. After a few minutes it flew across the marsh/beaver pond and called a few more times. It didn't respond to recordings (played between the two periods when I heard it). The wetland and adjacent trees are immediately behind a large warehouse. My second record for the county.
still quite young; no tail

Initially submitted as Black-billed Cuckoo/Yellow-billed Cuckoo. Had now been accepted by Ebird reviewer as Black billed Cuckoo. Pros for juvenile black: the all-black bill, pale orbital ring, and pale edging on the feathers.  Plus it seems a little late in the season for juvenile yellows to still have a black bill.  Pros for juvenile yellow: also the black bill, rufous patch on the wings, and black-billed is rare on the coast. Unfortunately didn't get a look at the undertail before it flew off.  We were clued into this bird by his call which was 3 notes and did not vary in pitch or cadence. Observed in line of trees across from spawar building before it flew onto a power line. After perching for a minute or so, it flew west and we could not relocate the bird. See pictures.

In cottonwoods south of the fourth sub-cell from the west (38.89444° N, 92.44392° W). This Black-billed Cuckoo was first heard calling and continued to call often and at length for more than 35 minutes, even while we were leaving the area. Playback should be avoided, especially because the bird may be on territory. If that's the case, a Yellow-billed Cuckoo might ultimately drive off the Black-billed Cuckoo. We can hope otherwise.

Photos TBA. **rarely seen and difficult-to-detect migrant. I believe this is a continuing immature first photographed by Alena and likely the slim, chestnut-brown body with wings lacking the intense rufous wing patch cuckoo I flushed a day or so prior to her seeing this bird. I'm sure he's come to know me well as I've searched for him unsuccessfully the last few days.  Slender, delicate and athletically built cuckoo, with darker brown tones to body, a hint of rufous to the wings, and a thin tail lacking conspicuous markings. Immature bird with pale yellow orbital ring. Slender all dark bill.  Caught a glimpse of movement as the bird came in high from the North, flushed by another entity which I did not observe.  Actually quite mobile, flying from tree to tree. Wary and shy of my presence but tolerating with slow and precise movements. At one point the bird flew from its high hickory into small dense trees about 15 feet off the ground and less distance than that away from me, providing a great experience! I lost track of it shortly after. Plenty of tent caterpillar nests around, but I did not witness him utilizing any. One of my favorite species! I hope to see an adult soon.

This gives a cleaner view of the bird...whole back, thinnish black bill and red eye ring.  Sorry for late addition but in all the excitement of trying to observe the bird this photo was taken at a different time than the others and was in with the yellow-billed cuckoo photos.)  Saw bird in good view perched but without camera.  Then refound buried in bush with camera.  Cuckoo with all black bill and red eye orbital.  Never saw underside of tail.  Bill was thinish.  No rufous visible on primaries from photo. A yellow billed cuckoo was in area ... but they did not interact like parent juvenile, and red eye ring  separates adult black billed from juvenile yellow billed. Locality: Montrose Point Bird Sanctuary, Lincoln Park, Chicago
Observation Details: Heard a typical "gow-gow-gow" a couple of times in the meadow area. Then saw this juvenile cuckoo (with outer tail feathers not fully grown) in an open tree. Watched it with Rob Hansen (visiting from CA) and concluded it was a juvenile Yellow-billed despite having some black-billed "characters" including yellowish throat and breast, dark bill, barring on upperparts, and a slim bill at some angles. YBCU may have bred here this year and this may be one of the young, but a Black-billed was apparently reported here yesterday which seems unusual given the time of year. Appreciate any comments on ID. UPDATE: After looking at many pictures on Ebird, the photographed bird matched juvenile BBCU, especially by the pale tips to coverts that are prominent on many BBCU and hardly or not present on YBCU. The undertail also has no white spots - thanks for comments by Amy Kearns and Matthew Cvetas.

One was vocalizing from the south side of -- and very close to -- the tracks, shortly past Prairie Road.  It alternated between the "cou cou cou" call and the other clucking call.  (This is the bird in the photos) At the same time, another bird was giving the "cou cou cou" call from the north side of the tracks, a little deeper into the woods; they seemed to go back and forth for a little while.  I watched the first bird for several minutes, after which it took off and headed southeast.  I was quite surprised to see another BBCU fly out of the same tree right behind it; maybe it was better hidden, or perhaps I was so focused on the first one that I hadn't noticed.  It was definitely a third bird, though, since the one in the woods to the north called again a few seconds later.

Continuing immature bird, just found by Liz Freeman here this morning, and less than 3.5 miles from home!  Seen at about 34.0240073, -84.0100301 in willow and small tree just behind it, and around the edges of the creek side clearing there, from the rough trail which comes from the manhole cover, standing at about 34.0238080, -84.0099520.  Relocated at about 10:21 and well observed until about 10:45, mostly eating giant caterpillars in the small tree behind the willow. - - - At one point the cuckoo perched in the open maybe 40-50 feet away totally unobstructed and facing me with its head turned perfectly to the side (I was thinking the way that Audubon would have painted it), for a pristine very close and full look at the young bird completely upright, absolutely exquisite and stunning (but did not pose there long enough for footage)!  - - - Slender brownish cuckoo with yellow-ochre eyering, smaller thinner gray to black bill, faintly buffy throat, upperpart feathers fringed/tipped pale, no detectable rufous in the wings, tail gray underneath with no tail spots but with pale gray feather tips. - - - Beware of Yellow-billed Cuckoo.  Gwinnett #235. Thanks Again Liz!!!

Observation Details: Photos TBA. **rarely seen and difficult-to-detect migrant. I believe this is a continuing immature first photographed by Alena and likely the slim, chestnut-brown body with wings lacking the intense rufous wing patch cuckoo I flushed a day or so prior to her seeing this bird. I'm sure he's come to know me well as I've searched for him unsuccessfully the last few days.  Slender, delicate and athletically built cuckoo, with darker brown tones to body, a hint of rufous to the wings, and a thin tail lacking conspicuous markings. Immature bird with pale yellow orbital ring. Slender all dark bill.  Caught a glimpse of movement as the bird came in high from the North, flushed by another entity which I did not observe.  Actually quite mobile, flying from tree to tree. Wary and shy of my presence but tolerating with slow and precise movements. At one point the bird flew from its high hickory into small dense trees about 15 feet off the ground and less distance than that away from me, providing a great experience! I lost track of it shortly after. Plenty of tent caterpillar nests around, but I did not witness him utilizing any. One of my favorite species! I hope to see an adult soon.

Observation Details: This was a difficult bird to identify because it is a juvenile. I knew I had to consider both species since they have both been in the area since the road was opened to the public. A juvenile Yellow-billed Cuckoo can lack most, if not all yellow on the bill. Due to the large amount of rufous on the primaries, I was leaning toward that species. However in "Birds of the World: "Juvenile Black-billed Cuckoo has cinnamon wash on primaries and yellowish orbital ring, both attributes as in adult Yellow-billed Cuckoo." I briefly saw the undertail but was unable to get a photo. It was rather plain gray and lacked the bold large white spots that should be seen on Yellow-billed Cuckoo of any age. Hence, this should be a juvenile Black-billed Cuckoo. There was no yellow whatsoever on the bill of this bird.

Observation Details: When the Black-billed Cuckoo first arrived, I mistook it for a Mourning Dove, on a bare treetop where Doves are often seen, so I didn't pay too much attention. When it flew over to the tree I was sitting near, the profile with the long tail alerted me to the fact it was NOT a dove! On the previous day, as I took pics of an approaching storm/wall cloud from Walmart's parking lot, I had captured the same silhouette unknowingly, so in retrospect, I realized that I had seen one of the 2 species already. This individual left after about 15-20 minutes and wasn't found again.

One was vocalizing from the south side of -- and very close to -- the tracks, shortly past Prairie Road.  It alternated between the "cou cou cou" call and the other clucking call.  (This is the bird in the photos) At the same time, another bird was giving the "cou cou cou" call from the north side of the tracks, a little deeper into the woods; they seemed to go back and forth for a little while.  I watched the first bird for several minutes, after which it took off and headed southeast.  I was quite surprised to see another BBCU fly out of the same tree right behind it; maybe it was better hidden, or perhaps I was so focused on the first one that I hadn't noticed.  It was definitely a third bird, though, since the one in the woods to the north called again a few seconds later.

Locality: Private Property - Noisy Creek - Town of Eau Pleine
Observation Details: I observed what I believe was courtship between this pair, but I also think they are visiting a probable nest site. I have, until today, known there was at least one BBCU in this area. Today I heard one call, and located it. I watched for several minutes. A second bird came out and followed the first one. I didn't notice until I looked at the photos on the computer, that the one that called was carrying a tiny caterpillar. Since that is part of their courtship ritual, I am reporting this as 'C Probable'. I do suspect they are visiting a probable nesting site, as they keep flying in to a large willow shrub, but will keep an eye on this area as it's on my property.

I spent a half hour following this bird around hoping to get a glimpse of the undertail, and never was able to do so. Called juvenile YBCU in the field but photographs show buffy throat, chest is white, eye ring was definitely yellow in the field as it shows in most of the photographs (some have a glare from sun that gives a hint of red). Lack of rufous tones in primaries apparent in photos even in varying light, and I never caught a hint of rufous when the bird flushed several times. Viewed with Tommy Maloney several times, which is ironic since it was Tommy who found my own lifer BBCU in May 2019 about 50 yards from this same location.

Update 10/14/21:  I found this interesting cuckoo along the levee trail behind Heron Pond during this same checklist session on Sep 27.  When looking at my pictures, noting the dark bill, I focused in on the pale "panels" in between the black spots on the underside of the tail.  I ticked this as a juvenile Yellow-billed Cuckoo.  However, since the 27th I've been looking at my photos at length and, while admittedly they are not the sharpest, I've seen more than I did at first:  **  The large "whitish panels" on the underside of the tail aren't necessarily big white spots; the tail is backlit which I think makes these areas appear much lighter than they really are. **  The eyering is pale but has a slightly greenish cast. **  The bill is black but the base of the lower mandible, while also dark, is silvery. **  The throat and upper breast are clearly buffy and contrast with the white belly. **  Upperside feathers have pale fringes. **  There are contrastingly blackish spots at the bottom of the "whitish panels."  Each one has a narrow white terminal band.  In addition, I reached out to Ted Floyd at the ABA and asked for his expert opinion.  He was kind enough to reply:  "I would go with Black-billed. It's got the mostly gray tail, the dark bill, and a buffy throat. Best, --TF"  So, I'm deleting Yellow-billed and adding Black-billed.

Initially assumed to be immature YB in field.  Upon review of pics, however, bird shows buffy throat, pale fringes on wing feathers, and partially gray bill consistent with Sibley's description of immature BB.  Immature BB also shows some rufous on wing, matching pics.  Bird appeared cold brown in flight, rufous not obvious in flight.  Immature YB lacks yellow on bill through Aug. according to Sibley, so YB should show some yellow by now.  Very bad pic showing bit of tail appears to show small white ticks consistent with BB.  Bird was found very low and seemed to prefer low cedars along path.  Flushed into deciduous when walkers came by.  After several minutes, returned to low cedars along path.  Pete Dunne's Field Guide companion notes that BB forages lower than YB.  VA Gold Book extreme date for BB is 10/24, much later than I'd have guessed.  Based on all above info, entering as BB.

Locality: Santee Delta WMA--East (fall and winter restricted access)
Observation Details: A long-tailed bird flew into a dense, vine-covered tree next to me. First thought was yellow-billed cuckoo, which I had seen in the area. But I did note that the wings looked concolor with the back. One diagnostic photo reveals a thinnish, all black bill and buffy throat. Orbital ring is a greenish-yellow, so perhaps a first year bird?

Update 10/14/21:  I found this interesting cuckoo along the levee trail behind Heron Pond during this same checklist session on Sep 27.  When looking at my pictures, noting the dark bill, I focused in on the pale "panels" in between the black spots on the underside of the tail.  I ticked this as a juvenile Yellow-billed Cuckoo.  However, since the 27th I've been looking at my photos at length and, while admittedly they are not the sharpest, I've seen more than I did at first:  **  The large "whitish panels" on the underside of the tail aren't necessarily big white spots; the tail is backlit which I think makes these areas appear much lighter than they really are. **  The eyering is pale but has a slightly greenish cast. **  The bill is black but the base of the lower mandible, while also dark, is silvery. **  The throat and upper breast are clearly buffy and contrast with the white belly. **  Upperside feathers have pale fringes. **  There are contrastingly blackish spots at the bottom of the "whitish panels."  Each one has a narrow white terminal band.  In addition, I reached out to Ted Floyd at the ABA and asked for his expert opinion.  He was kind enough to reply:  "I would go with Black-billed. It's got the mostly gray tail, the dark bill, and a buffy throat. Best, --TF"  So, I'm deleting Yellow-billed and adding Black-billed.

Observation Details: I heard one vocalize briefly at 20:09 and got a marginal recording, which appears at the end of the wood thrush recording below.  At 20:18 one vocalized again with the "kowp, kowp, kowp" sounds and almost immediately afterward the second made some of the same sounds (and some different ones, which are somewhat like growls) from a different direction. The birds were separated by roughly 50 meters. Both birds were on the north side of the road and apparently near the edge of the wetland. Not seen. The recording below begins with a common yellowthroat song. The first cuckoo vocalizes while the yellowthroat sings and then within seconds the second cuckoo starts.    Initially identified as yellow-billed cuckoo but changed to black-billed after checking other recordings.

Patch species #204.  For those considering looking for this bird, I would suggest an early morning or late evening visit, if possible. It is more likely that the cuckoo will be active and vocalizing at these times. Also—and importantly—you may avoid a scenario in which you find yourself dragging your body up a sun-scorched coulee face at 36° wishing for the sweet release of death just a little more with each pitiful step.

My FOS. I've walked this trail each day since Daniel Danza reported the bird here. Bird first made some gurgling noises that I was sure was a cuckoo, but couldn't say which. About a minute later it gave a kyulp call and I knew it was a Black-billed. It gave the same call every half minute or so until I finally found it in the dense leaves. It then got quite confiding, coming out and moving freely back and forth across the trail. It never gave the typical CuCuCu call.

Another bird was seen closer to the parking area on the way back, which landed a smaller tree alongside the path.  Adult Black-billed Cuckoos have a red orbital ring and because of this resemble Killdeer in the eye. Adult  Yellow-billed Cuckoo have a yellow orbital ring in addition to a yellow bill.
